DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(75)90039-2
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199675900392
AB  - Tariffs and quotas are compared as instruments for restricting imports to improve the terms of trade in a world in which domestic and/or foreign supply and demand conditions are stochastic. The two instruments are not generally equivalent in their welfare effects, and furthermore there is no general presumption in favour of one instrument over the other. In a particular model, characterized by linear supply and demand curves for imports, quotas are more likely to be superior when the predominant source of uncertainty is with respect to foreign supply conditions and when the supply of imports is inelastic.
